[{"id":31556,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>In given ionic compound anions form&nbsp;CCP lattice, And&nbsp;cation is&nbsp;present in octahedral void. Means this structure is similar to structure of NaCl. Which is also called rock salt structure.</p><p>Edge length =&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>?</mo></math></p><p>In rock salt structure cations and anions are in contact along the edge of the cube.&nbsp;</p><p>So,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>+</mo></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>-</mo></msub></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mfenced><mrow><mn>102</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>181</mn></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mfenced><mn>283</mn></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>566</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>pm</mi></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31612,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["Sulphur","Phosphorus","Iodine","Silicon"],"answer":3,"solution":"Silicon is covalent or network solid.<br /><br />Each Si atom is in sp<sup>3&nbsp;</sup>hybridisation.<br /><br />Sulphur (S<sub>8</sub>)&nbsp; &ndash;&nbsp; molecular solid.<br /><br />Phosphorus (P<sub>4</sub>)&nbsp; &ndash;&nbsp;molecular solid.<br /><br />Iodine (I<sub>2</sub>)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ndash;&nbsp; molecular solid.<br />&nbsp;","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (07 Apr)","image":null},{"id":31561,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Given: Molar mass of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>AB</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow></mfenced><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><mtable columnalign=\"left\"><mtr><mtd><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo><mi>Atomicwt</mi><mo>.</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>of</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo><mi>Atomicwt</mi><mo>.</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>of</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo></math> atomic wt. of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math> is 2 times of atomic wt. of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math> Integer answer is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>.</p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (27 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31575,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><msub><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>MA</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>In HCP unit cell number of effective number of atoms is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn></math>,</p><p>so&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn></math>.</p><p>Number of tetrahedral voids</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo></math>&nbsp;2 x number of&nbsp;atoms forming the lattice&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo></math><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>6</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mrow><mn>12</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow><mn>6</mn></msub></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mn>8</mn></msub><msub><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow><mn>6</mn></msub></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><msub><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow><mn>3</mn></msub></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (18 Mar Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31621,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["$30 \\%$ and $26 \\%$","$26 \\%$ and $32 \\%$","$32 \\%$ and $48 \\%$","$48 \\%$ and $26 \\%$"],"answer":1,"solution":"Packing fraction of cubic close packing and body centred packing are $0.74$ and $0.68$ respectively.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2010","image":null},{"id":31602,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["<math><mn>0.93</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Å</mi></math>","<math><mn>1.86</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&nbsp;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Å</mi></math>","<math><mn>3.22</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Å</mi></math>","<math><mn>5.72</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Å</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>For B.C.C lattice,<br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mn>4</mn> <mtext>r</mtext> <mo>=</mo> <msqrt> <mn>3</mn> </msqrt> <mtext>a</mtext> </mrow> </math></p><p>where&nbsp;&#39;r&#39; is radius of atom and &#39;a&#39; is edge length of unit cell<br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mtext>r</mtext> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <msqrt> <mn>3</mn> </msqrt> </mrow> <mrow> <mn>4</mn> </mrow> </mfrac> <mtext>a</mtext> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mtext>1.732</mtext> </mrow> <mrow> <mn>4</mn> </mrow> </mfrac> <mo>&#215;</mo> <mtext>4.29</mtext> </mrow> </math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mo>=</mo> <mtext>1.86</mtext> <mi>&#197;</mi> </mrow> </math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2015 (04 Apr)","image":null},{"id":31570,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mfenced><mfrac><mi>gm</mi><mi>cc</mi></mfrac></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></msub></mfrac></mrow><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi><msup><mo>)</mo><mn>3</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>7</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>62</mn><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>/</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>022</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>23</mn></msup></mrow><msup><mfenced><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4518</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>7</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>3</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>105</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>mol</mi></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (22 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31548,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Bravais Lattice refers to the 14 different 3-dimensional configurations into which atoms can be arranged in crystals. The smallest group of symmetrically aligned atoms which can be repeated in an array to make up the entire crystal is called a unit cell. Crystal systems where body centred unit cell can be found are Cubic, orthorhombic and tetragonal</p><p>Hence, correct answer is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (06 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31601,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>FCC</mi><mo>&#160;</mo></math>unit cell: eight corners with six faces</p><p>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"/><mn>4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"/><mi>Closest</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>distance</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>in</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>fcc</mi><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"/><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"/><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfrac><mrow><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></mrow><mrow><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt><mo>&#215;</mo><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt></mfrac></math></p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2017 (02 Apr)","image":null},{"id":31629,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["4 and 2","9 and 14","14 and 9","2 and 4"],"answer":3,"solution":"BCC - points are at corners and one in the centre of the unit cell\nNumber of atoms per unit cell $=8 \\times \\frac{1}{8}+1=2$\nFCC - points are at the corners and also centre of the six faces of each cell\nNumber of atoms per unit cell $=8 \\times \\frac{1}{8}+6 \\times \\frac{1}{2}=4$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2002","image":null},{"id":31627,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["super-cooled liquid","gel","polymeric mixture","micro-crystalline solid"],"answer":0,"solution":"Glass is a transparent or translucent super cooled liquid.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2003","image":null},{"id":31591,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["0.027 a","0.047 a","$0.134 \\mathrm{a}$","0.067 a"],"answer":3,"solution":"For bcc\r\n\r\n$$\r\n\r\n\\Rightarrow \\mathrm{R}=\\frac{\\sqrt{3} \\mathrm{a}}{4}\r\n\r\n$$\r\n\r\n$$\r\n\r\n\\therefore \\text { Empty space at edge }=a-2 R=a-\\frac{\\sqrt{3} a}{2}\r\n\r\n$$\r\n\r\n$=$ diameter of sphere.\r\n\r\n$$\r\n\r\n\\therefore \\quad \\mathrm{r}_{\\text {sphere }}=\\frac{a-\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2} \\mathrm{a}}{2}=\\left(\\frac{2-\\sqrt{3}}{4}\\right) \\mathrm{a}=0.067 \\mathrm{a}\r\n\r\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (11 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31572,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math> is true but <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></math> is false","Both <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></math> are true but <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></math> is NOT the correct<br />explanation of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>.</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math> is false but <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></math> is true.","Both <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></math> are true and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></math> is the correct explanation of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>."],"answer":1,"solution":"Sharp glass edges are heated to make them smooth. Because on heating glass melts and the surface of the liquid tends to take the rounded shape at the edges which has minimum surface area. This is called fire polishing of glass. Correct explanation for this is surface tension.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (20 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31618,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["$75 \\mathrm{~pm}$","$300 \\mathrm{~pm}$","$240 \\mathrm{~pm}$","$152 \\mathrm{~pm}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"For BCC, $\\sqrt{3} a=4 r$\n$r=\\frac{\\sqrt{3} \\times 351}{4}=152 \\mathrm{~pm}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (Offline)","image":null},{"id":31576,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mole</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>KBr</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>119</mn><mi>gm</mi><mo>)</mo></math> have <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup><mn>100</mn></mfrac></math> moles <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>SrBr</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;and hence, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>7</mn></mrow></msup></math> moles cation vacancy (as <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><msup><mi>Sr</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></math> will result <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math> cation vacancy)</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo></math> Required number of cation vacancies</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>7</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>023</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>23</mn></msup></mrow><mn>119</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>06</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>14</mn></msup><mo>&#8771;</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>14</mn></msup></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (17 Mar Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31571,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Carbon atoms occupy FCC lattice points as well as half of the tetrahedral voids</p><p>therefore number of carbon atoms atoms per unit cell <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>8</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (20 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31611,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["$0.56 \\mathrm{~nm}$","$0.24 \\mathrm{~nm}$","$0.96 \\mathrm{~nm}$","$0.4 \\mathrm{~nm}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"For a fcc unit cell\n$\\begin{aligned}\n& r=\\frac{\\sqrt{2} a}{4} \\\\\n& a=\\frac{4 r}{\\sqrt{2}}=2 \\sqrt{2} \\times 0.14=0.39 \\approx 0.4 \\mathrm{~nm}.\n\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (09 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":31573,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>SiO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Mn</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Na</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>MgO</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Mn</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math> shows magnetic properties.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (18 Mar Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31622,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["$108 \\mathrm{pm}$","$127 \\mathrm{pm}$","157 pm","$181 \\mathrm{pm}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"For FCC,\n$\\sqrt{2} a=4 r$ (the atoms touches each other along the face- diagonal)\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& r=\\frac{\\sqrt{2} a}{4}=\\frac{\\sqrt{2} \\times 361}{4} \\\\\n& =127 \\mathrm{pm}\n\\end{aligned}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2009","image":null},{"id":31604,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{a}=\\mathrm{b} \\neq \\mathrm{c}$ and $\\alpha=\\beta=\\gamma=90^{\\circ}$","a $\\neq$ b $\\neq$ c and $\\alpha=\\beta=\\gamma=90^{\\circ}$","$\\mathrm{a} \\neq \\mathrm{b} \\neq \\mathrm{c}$ and $\\beta=\\gamma=90^{\\circ} \\neq \\alpha$","$\\mathrm{a} \\neq \\mathrm{b} \\neq \\mathrm{c}$ and $\\alpha \\neq \\beta \\neq \\gamma \\neq 90^{\\circ}$"],"answer":2,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (12 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":31565,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"In <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math><br />Effective number of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math> atoms <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn></math> (in CCP)<br />Effective number of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math> atoms <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn></math> (all O.V.)<br />So formula of the compound <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>AB</mi></math><br />So <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (31 Aug Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31554,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>From the diagram of voids in HCP:<br /><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f1bac7f5-f4bd-45bc-9082-80ccb084d85b-16.PNG\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 221px;\" /><br />There are 6 octahedral voids and 12 tetrahedral voids in a HCP unit cell.<br />One unit cell of HCP contains <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>18</mn></math>&nbsp;voids</p><p>Thus, No. of voids in <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mol</mi></math> of hcp</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>18</mn><mn>6</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>23</mn></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8776;</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>22</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8776;</mo><mn>36</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>21</mn></msup></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (29 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31628,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["$5.14 \\times 10^{21}$ unit cells","$1.28 \\times 10^{21}$ unit cells","$1.71 \\times 10^{21}$ unit cells","$2.57 \\times 10^{21}$ unit cells"],"answer":3,"solution":"Number of formulas in cube shaped crystals $=\\frac{1.0}{58.5} \\times 6.02 \\times 10^{23}$ since in $\\mathrm{NaCl}$ type of structure 4 formula units form a cell\n$\\therefore$ unit cells $=\\frac{1.0 \\times 6.02 \\times 10^{23}}{58.5 \\times 4}=2.57 \\times 10^{21}$ unit cells.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2003","image":null},{"id":31589,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["<math><mn>90</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">%</mi></math>","<math><mn>45</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">%</mi></math>","<math><mn>75</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">%</mi></math>","<math><mn>65</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">%</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d56858d2-34ef-457b-b322-d2b27b5e8080-image.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 217px;\" /></p><p>If radius of <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math> is <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></math> radius of <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math> will be <math><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></math> . Atoms in the body diagonal touch.</p><p>Therefore:<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></math></p><p><math><mn>6</mn><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></math> or <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>6</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></mrow><mrow><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p>Packing Efficiency<br /><math><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi><msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>9</mn></mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mn>6</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>/</mo><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mo>)</mo></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><math><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>3</mn><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>216</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>90.5</mn><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">%</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (08 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31552,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Let number of ions of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mrow><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi></math></p><p>Thus, as net charge has to be zero,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mrow><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>83</mn><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>(</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>83</mn><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>(</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>49</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>49</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>%</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup><mtext>&#160;ions&#160;</mtext><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>49</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>83</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>59</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>03</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (31 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31578,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>For <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>BCC</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></math></p><p>so&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>27</mn></math></p><p>for <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>FCC</mi><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>27</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>27</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>33</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (16 Mar Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31566,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iv</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iii</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iv</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iv</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iv</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Antiferromagnetism, type of magnetism in solids&nbsp;in which adjacent ions that behave as tiny magnets</p><p>Paramagnetism&nbsp;is a form of magnetism whereby some materials are weakly attracted by an externally applied magnetic field, and form internal, induced magnetic fields in the direction of the applied magnetic field.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>MnO</mi></math>- Antiferromagnetism<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>- Paramagnetism<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NaCl</mi></math>- Diamagnetism<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Fe</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>- Ferrimagnetism</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Aug Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31603,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["1","2","3","4"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>In CCP there are four atoms per unit cell octahedral voids are<br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>12</mn><mfenced><mtext>Edge centres</mtext></mfenced><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mfenced><mtext>Body centre</mtext></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>.</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mo>.</mo></math>&nbsp;[Contribution at edge centre is<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac></math> ]</p><p>Four octahedral voids are present in a unit cell i.e. four atoms.</p><p>Therefore, per atom one octahedral void will be present.</p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (19 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":31560,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>In <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Fe</mi><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>93</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math> for every <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>93</mn><mi>Fe</mi></math> ions <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>14</mn></math>&nbsp;are <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Fe</mi><mrow><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mn>93</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>14</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>79</mn></math> are <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Fe</mi><mrow><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math> ions</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>%</mo><msup><mi>Fe</mi><mrow><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>79</mn><mn>93</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>84</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>%</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo></math> nearest integer&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>85</mn><mo>%</mo></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (27 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31557,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Given ,<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>8</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>03</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>ml</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>ZM</mi><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p>Volume of a unit cell = a<sup>3</sup>, where a is the edge length</p><p><strong>d</strong> is the density of the solid substance and<strong> M</strong> is the molar mass.</p><p>Mass of the unit cell = number of atoms in unit cell &times; mass of each atom =<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math></p><p>(Here z is the number of atoms present in one unit cell and m is the mass of a single atom)<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>9</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>03</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>23</mn></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>64</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>24</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>86</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>97</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>mol</mi></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (28 Jul Shift 2)","image":nu